{
  "doc_id": "49064",
  "text": "To date, a limited number of GPCRs have been shown to interact (directly or indirectly) with EGFR. Recently, it was discovered that the vasopressin 1A receptor, a G q -coupled receptor also interacts with EGFR by co-immunoprecipitation studies, although how this interaction affects signaling of either receptor is unknown [CITATION_1] . The b1-adrenergic receptor has been shown to interact with EGFR by coimmunoprecipitation and FRET analysis under basal conditions [CITATION_2] . Treatment of cells with the b1-adrenergic receptor agonist, isoproterenol, did not affect FRET efficiency when compared to untreated cells [CITATION_3] . We also found that EGF treatment promoted the internalization of GPR54 in breast cancer cells and that GPR54 and EGFR partially co-localized upon treatment of Kp-10 or EGF. Similar observations have been reported with b2-adrenergic receptor which co-localized with EGFR in response to isoproterenol stimulation [CITATION_4] . Thus, although many GPCRs can transactivate EGFR [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , the association with EGFR appears to be unique to a subset of GPCRs. For example, activation of the angiotensin receptor (AT 1A R) can also transactivate EGFR, however this receptor does not complex with EGFR [CITATION_8] .",
